## 6. Launch a device on a remote host (SSH)

The device process is just a Python script that needs the creds file plus
network access to the {{ broker_label }}. Quick start with tmux (survives the SSH disconnect):

```bash
# 1. Provision (locally) and copy the creds file + script to the edge host.
dc-portalctl devices provision cam-001 --device-type camera \
    --creds-output-file ./{{ tenant }}-cam-001.creds.json
scp ./{{ tenant }}-cam-001.creds.json my_device.py user@edge-host:~/dc/

# 2. One-time per host: create a dedicated venv and install device-connect-edge.
#    Using a venv (rather than `pip install --user`) pins the interpreter
#    so the systemd unit in Appendix B can call it directly — `/usr/bin/python3`
#    on Homebrew/pyenv hosts won't see `--user` site-packages.
#    `nkeys` is pulled in as a required dep; no need to list it separately.
ssh user@edge-host "python3 -m venv ~/.dc-edge && \
                    ~/.dc-edge/bin/pip install --upgrade pip && \
                    ~/.dc-edge/bin/pip install --upgrade device-connect-edge"

# 3. Run it in a detached tmux session, using the venv's interpreter.
ssh user@edge-host "tmux new -d -s dc-cam-001 \
    'cd ~/dc && \
     {{ creds_env }}=./{{ tenant }}-cam-001.creds.json \
{% if is_mqtt -%}
     MQTT_URL=mqtt://{{ public_host }}:{{ broker_port }} \
{%- elif not is_zenoh -%}
     NATS_URL=nats://{{ public_host }}:{{ broker_port }} \
{%- endif %}
     ~/.dc-edge/bin/python my_device.py 2>&1 | tee dc-cam-001.log'"

# 4. Verify from the portal side.
dc-portalctl devices list | grep {{ tenant }}-cam-001
```

For long-lived deployments, use a systemd-user unit so the service
auto-restarts — see [Appendix B](#appendix-b-systemd-deployment).

